        }
      ],
      "description": "The guards of [[Nervios]]\r\n\r\n- Patrolling the city 24/7 on a schedule\r\n    \r\n- Guards move around in groups \r\n    \r\n- Respected by the general population, but also slightly feared\r\n    \r\n-   \r\n    \r\n- Different types of guards\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Internal Guards:\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Less trained than other branches of military with less powerful weaponry\r\n    \r\n- Underground tunnel system connecting towers\r\n    \r\n- Guard towers around the city on the walls\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Towers can’t be seen into from the outside\r\n    \r\n- Citizens don’t know if a tower is manned or not\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Guard towers throughout the interior of city\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Underground tunnels connecting them\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Maybe they have eyes that impose crippling fear on those who don't belong? (Poisoned in 5e)\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Allows for fast deployment of guards to any point in the city\r\n    \r\n- Outsiders can’t see in – acts as a panopticon\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Maintains the peace, even if a guard isn’t in that specific tower\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Nicknamed “Eyes” by locals/rebellion\r\n    \r\n- Tiers of guards:\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Junior\r\n    \r\n- Senior\r\n    \r\n- Captain \r\n    \r\n\r\n- Some loyal to the King, some the Government, some the rich, sizable amount are loyal to anyone who pays money\r\n\r\n\r\n- Army\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Snipers\r\n    \r\n- Infantry\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Navy\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Warships\r\n    \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\n- Watchman:\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Guard the walls and docks from outside threats\r\n    \r\n- Controls who enters/exits the cities\r\n    \r\n- Thoroughly inspects incoming/exiting cargo \r\n    \r\n\r\n- Corrupted?\r\n    \r\n\r\n- Some guards might use their status and position to disobey laws or take advantage of others. \r\n    \r\n\r\n- Creates resentment and fear of all guards\r\n    \r\n- PLOTLINE: Players start as junior guards and witness a fellow guard breaking the law. They are put into a position where they must decide between what's morally right, and the approval/protection of their peers.\r\n    \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nDamaged old tower which falls apart/players explore and find out that not all towers are functional.",
